Introduction¶

In this project we have analized some of the data collected on the web site http://www.gapminder.org/data/. On this page we can find a lot of information referred to many countries (economical, social, geographical, etc), but we have focused in some data related with health. Expecifically, we have estudied the data related with health expenditures (public and private), life expectancy, and the data gathered about some cancer types.

The total number of countries with data collected are 197.

Question 1: What Is The Influence Of The Ratio Private/Total Health Expenditure In The Life Expectancy And In The Cancer Treatments Success?¶

Some countries have a strong public health system and the investment in health care comes mainly from the goverment, while others confide more in private institutions to solve the health issues. We would like to compare both cases, analyzing the percentage of private investments in each country and comparing them with the life expectancy and the rate of deaths by cancer causes for each country. The analisys was made for 2010.

Question 2: Compare The Increment In Total Health Spending Between 1995 and 2010 With The Increment In The Life Expectancy And Healing Cancer Ratios During These Years.¶

We are also interested in knowing how the total investments in health have grown in the last years. In which regions of the world have increased more and in which have increased less. We want also to compare this values with the increment of the life expectancy and the percentage of deaths by cancer. Which regions have had a better behaviour?

We would also like to know how much is the mean increment in the total health spending for one year of increment in the life expectancy. This value will be calculated depending on the life expectancy. I mean, It is not the same to increase one year if the life expectancy is 60 than if the life expectancy is 70.

This increments were avaluated for the years 1995 and 2010.

Question 3: Relation Between The Cancer Types And The Region Of The World Or The Human Development Index (HDI).¶

In this part we have studied the correlation between the types of cancer, the region of the world and the HDI, if there is any. We want to know which cancer type causes more deaths in each region of the world.

The regions will be evaluated by geographical areas, but we will make also the research dividing the countries by HDI (Human Development Index). We are also interested in knowing how is the behaviour in coutries with less development and compare them with those with a higher index. Are some types of cancer more usual in coutries with hight HDI?, whereas, which ones are more frequent in contries with low development?

We have analized this data for two years, 1995 and 2015, to observe any difference.

Data Wrangling¶

General Properties¶

Data Types:¶

All the loaded dataframes have the seme structure:

  • The country is used as index for rows and each year represents a column in the dataframe.

  • year and country, are both as strings.

  • The values are all float64.

  • The meaning of the data is indicated in the name of the file or the dataframe.

Data Description:¶

This is the description of the values according to the gapminder page.

  • year: The year in which the values were taken.
  • country: The country for each value.

  • hdi: Human development index. Is an index used to rank the countries by level of 'human development'. It contains three dimnensions: health level, educational level, and living standard.

  • life_expectancy: The average number of years a newborn child would live if current mortality patterns were to stay the same.

  • gov_health_spend: The average health expenditure per person that has been paid by gobernment entities, expressed in US dollars using the exchange rate.

  • total_health_spend: The average health expenditure per person, expressed in US dollars using the average exchange rate.

  • private_health_spend: Private share of health expenditure (%). Percentage of total health expenditure that has been paid by private entities, for exampel commercial insurance and out-of-pocket payments.

  • breast_cancer_deaths_w, cervical_cancer_deaths_w, colonandrectum_cancer_deaths_w, liver_cancer_deaths_w, lung_cancer_deaths_w, stomach_cancer_deaths_w, colonandrectum_cancer_deaths_m, liver_cancer_deaths_m, lung_cancer_deaths_m, prostate_cancer_deaths_m, stomach_cancer_deaths_m: Number of deaths due to each type of cancer in 100,000 male or female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

  • breast_cancer_new_cases_w, cervical_cancer_new_cases_w, colonandrectum_cancer_new_cases_w, liver_cancer_new_cases_w, lung_cancer_new_cases_w, stomach_cancer_new_cases_w, colonandrectum_cancer_new_cases_m, liver_cancer_new_cases_m, lung_cancer_new_cases_m, prostate_cancer_new_cases_m, stomach_cancer_new_cases_m: Number new cases due to each type of cancer in 100,000 male or female residents during the certain year. This rate is calculated as if each country has the same age composition as the world population.

df_regions description: This dataframe is a little different:

  • The country column acts as the index of the dataframe. It has also four more columns dividing the countries in regions:

  • four_regions: ['africa', 'americas', 'asia', 'europe']

  • six_regions: ['middle_east_north_africa', 'sub_saharan_africa', 'america',

     'south_asia', 'europe_central_asia', 'east_asia_pacific']

  • eight_regions: ['africa_north', 'africa_sub_saharan', 'america_north',

     'america_south', 'asia_west', 'east_asia_pacific', 'europe_east',
 'europe_west']

  • nine_regions: ['africa_north', 'africa_sub_saharan', 'america_central',

     'america_north', 'america_south', 'asia_west', 'east_asia_pacific',
 'europe_east', 'europe_west']

All the datatypes are strings. In any case we only have used the nine_regions division.

dfs1 = [dfs[key].melt(id_vars=["country"], var_name = "year", value_name = key) for key in dfs]

#It performs a merge of all the data frames included in the previous list.

df_global = reduce(lambda left,right: pd.merge(left,right,on=['country', 'year'],
                                               how='outer'), dfs1).sort_values(by=['country', 'year'])

#It performs a separeted merge with the dataframe regions. That is because regions doesn't have the column year. 
#The countries are grouped in differente regions.

df_global = df_global.merge(df_regions, left_on=['country'], right_on=['country'], how='outer')

Adding New Columns¶

  • It adds some additional columns calculated from the original data. For example we calculate the private health expenditure per person in US dollars using the percent value in private_health_spend_pc column. It also adds columns with the totals of cancer deaths and cases, summing the corresponding columns.

#It calculates the value of total dollars spended in private health for 100K habitants 
#using the percentage value 'private_health_spend_pc'

df_global['private_health_spend'] = round(df_global['private_health_spend_pc'] * df_global['total_health_spend'] / 100, 2)

#It adds a column with the total cancer deaths for men.

cancer_men_list_death = ['colonandrectum_cancer_deaths_m', 
                         'liver_cancer_deaths_m', 
                         'lung_cancer_deaths_m', 
                         'prostate_cancer_deaths_m', 
                         'stomach_cancer_deaths_m']

df_global['total_cancer_men_death'] = df_global[cancer_men_list_death].sum(axis=1)

#It adds a column with the total cancer deaths for women.

cancer_women_list_death = ['breast_cancer_deaths_w', 
                           'cervical_cancer_deaths_w', 
                           'colonandrectum_cancer_deaths_w', 
                           'liver_cancer_deaths_w', 
                           'lung_cancer_deaths_w',
                           'stomach_cancer_deaths_w']

df_global['total_cancer_women_death'] = df_global[cancer_women_list_death].sum(axis=1)

#It adds a column with the total cancer cases for men.

cancer_men_list_cases = ['colonandrectum_cancer_new_cases_m', 
                         'liver_cancer_new_cases_m', 
                         'lung_cancer_new_cases_m', 
                         'prostate_cancer_new_cases_m', 
                         'stomach_cancer_new_cases_m']

df_global['total_cancer_men_cases'] = df_global[cancer_men_list_cases].sum(axis=1)

#It adds a column with the total cancer cases for women.

cancer_women_list_cases = ['breast_cancer_new_cases_w', 
                           'cervical_cancer_new_cases_w', 
                           'colonandrectum_cancer_new_cases_w', 
                           'liver_cancer_new_cases_w', 
                           'lung_cancer_new_cases_w',
                           'stomach_cancer_new_cases_w']

df_global['total_cancer_women_cases'] = df_global[cancer_women_list_cases].sum(axis=1)

#It sums both cases for women and men.

df_global['total_cancer_cases'] = df_global['total_cancer_women_cases'] + df_global['total_cancer_men_cases']
df_global['total_cancer_death'] = df_global['total_cancer_women_death'] + df_global['total_cancer_men_death']

#It calculates year by year the difference and percentage betwen total new cases and deaths. It gives us an estimation of the
#treatments against cancer success.

df_global['total_cancer_heal'] = df_global['total_cancer_cases'] - df_global['total_cancer_death']
df_global['total_cancer_heal_pc'] = round((df_global['total_cancer_cases'] - df_global['total_cancer_death']) 
                                          / df_global['total_cancer_cases'] * 100, 2)

Research Question 1: What Is The Influence Of The Ratio Private/Total Health Expenditure In The Life Expectancy And In The Cancer Treatments Success?¶

  • In this first question we are going to explore the differences between the public and private health investments. We are interested in knowing how relevant are they in reaching a high life expectancy and in the succeess of the treatments against cancer. Are more successful those countries with a higher public spending or those with a higher private health spending?

    To make this aproach we are going to start depicting a graph with the percentage of the private health spending over the total spending based in the years of life expectancy. In the x-axis we are going to divide the countries by life expectancy years in four quartiles. The first quartile represents the countries with smallest life expectancy and the last quartile corresponds with the countries with a highest number of years. We are going to use the dataframe df_health1 filtered for the year 2010.

    The table and the graph with the results are showed below:

In [24]:

Research Question 3: Relation Between The Cancer Types And The Region Of The World Or The HDI (Human Development Index).¶

  • In this part we are interested in knowing if there are some correlation between the HDI or the region of the world and the different cancer types.

    To analyze that we are going to investigate which is the most usual cause of cancer death in each region or in each group of HDI. The calculations will be made for 1995 and 2015. That will permit us to find out any difference between regions and see if there has been any change with time.

    We are going to start with the analysis by the Human Development Index (HDI). We separate the countries in quartiles again by the HDI. Then, it is calculated the mean of deaths in each quartile for each type of cancer. We select the causes with more deaths in each quartile and it is showed in a dataframe and in a bar plot. The analisys will be mado for both years.

In [39]:

Conclusions¶

Conclusion 1:¶

From this analisys we can conclude that those countries with a greater life expectancy and with better results in cancer treatments tend, in general, to priorize the public health investments over the private investments. Whereas those countries with a high percentage of private health spending ususally have poorer results, probably because the total spending is very low in most of this cases. Anyway it seems that the responsability of achieve the higher marks in terms of health care belongs to the public investments, at least for the majority of the countries with the best results.

The best rate between private and total spending seems to be between 20% and 30%.

Conclusion 2:¶

We have seen here that Nort America and West Europe are the two regiong that have increased more, by far, the total spending in health between the years 1995 and 2010. And though their results have not been bad, they don't have experimented the greatest increments in the life expectancy or cancer treatment success . Probably because they already had high health standards before.

On the other hand, Subsaharian Africa had a very low increment in the health costs by person, but they have experimented a big increment in the life expectancy. But they don't have as good results in terms of cancer healing percentage, which continue to be very low.

Anyway I have doubts about the cancer data collected in the Subsaharian Africa, they probably are incomplete and they don't reflect all the actual cases.

Conclusion 3:¶

In this part we have found out that not all the types of cancer are so usual in all regions of the planet. In general, the lung cancer in men is the most frecuent type of cancer in almost all regions, but in Subsaharian Africa, Central America and South America, the prostate cancer seems to be the most frequent. We also have seen that, in the case os Subsaharian Africa, the cervical cancer was the most common in 1995.

We have also discovered that there is a correlation between some types of cancer and the human develpment index. In some types the number of deaths tends to increase with the HDI: as in the colon-rectum and lung cancer, while in other cases tends to be lower: as in prostate and cervical cancer. Int these cases the correlations is quite strong, which means that colon-rectum and lung cancer have more incidence in higher developed countries while prostate and lung cancer are a bigger problem in the coutries with lower development.

There are also some types of cancer that have not almost correlation.

This can be due to the access to the cancer treatments and to the life expectancy, because some types of cancer are more usual at advanced ages.
